<TEXT>
the top soviet arms control negotiator today said 
his nation and the united states have made modest progress toward 
an agreement on reducing longrange nuclear weapons since the 
moscow summit in june 
but the negotiator alexei obukhov also told the 40nation 
geneva conference on disarmament that there is a great amount of 
work that yet has to be done to resolve outstanding issues 
the arms control negotiators returned to geneva on july 12 to 
resume talks on a treaty to reduce longrange or strategic 
nuclear forces by 50 percent they are also working on a document 
governing defense and space issues 
obukhov said the very first weeks of the current negotiating 
round have already seen certain progress one has to be 
selfcritical however the progress achieved is very modest 
he said the soviet side has introduced a whole range of 
proposals at the talks during the past three weeks and is waiting 
for a us response 
a us official speaking on condition of anonymity said the 
us side also has been offering proposals during the talks what 
both delegations are engaged in is seeing how progress at the 
moscow summit can be reflected here in specific treaty language 
he told the associated press 
obukhov said one main issue at the arms talks is compliance with 
the 1972 antiballistic missile treaty and he indicated that the 
us strategic defense initiative program or sdi remains an 
obstacle 
obukhov reaffirmed the soviet position that a strategic arms 
treaty or start should be linked to an agreement assuring that 
development and deployment of strategic defenses such as sdi does 
not violate the abm treaty 
he reiterated the soviet position that a broad interpretation of 
the abm treaty which the reagan administration says would permit 
sdi development was not feasible 
another outstanding issue obukhov said is limitations on 
submarinelaunched cruise missiles which the soviets want included 
in the treaty the us opposes including such weapons in the 
treaty because it says it would be too difficult to prevent 
cheating 
obukhov said the two sides are working on four joint draft texts 
at the start talks the treaty a memorandum of understanding a 
protocol on inspection and a protocol on conversion and 
elimination of systems 
in december president reagan and mikhail s gorbachev signed a 
treaty eliminating all intermediaterange nuclear weapons the pact 
was ratified by both countries before the two leaders held the 
moscow summit in june 
</TEXT>
