<TEXT>
us businesses efficiency in producing goods 
and services decreased in the second quarter its first decline 
since 1986 the labor department said today 
preliminary data show productivity among nonfarm businesses 
responsible for threefourths of the nations economic activity 
falling 17 percent from april through june compared with the first 
three months of the year the department said 
productivity had risen at an annual rate of 34 percent from 
january through march 
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater commented the second 
quarter decline in productivity should be a temporary blip related 
to the drought so it shows the economy is still strong 
reflecting the continuing strong economic expansion output of 
goods and services by nonfarm businesses rose at an annual rate of 
47 percent in the second quarter 
to achieve that workers put in 65 percent more hours the 
largest quarterly increase since 1984 and a reflection of the 
14year low in the nations unemployment rate 
meanwhile labor costs soared 59 percent the largest gain 
since a 61 percent increase in the last quarter of 1986 as hourly 
wages and benefits rose at an annual rate of 41 percent in the 
second quarter 
after taking into consideration a 44 percent annual rate of 
inflation over the last 18 months however workers purchasing 
power actually declined 06 percent from april through june the 
department said 
while businesses as a whole suffered from poorer efficiency in 
the second quarter manufacturers responsible for a fourth of the 
nations economic output continued to show improved productivity 
up 35 percent from the first quarter 
reflecting an ongoing boom in the industrial sector spawned by 
record exports manufacturing output soared 54 percent in the 
second quarter with only a 18 percent increase in the number of 
hours worked 
manufacturers also were much more successful in holding down 
factory wage and benefit increases allowing annual raises of only 
29 percent from april through june 
that enabled employers to actually reduce the labor costs 
associated with each item coming off their assembly lines by 06 
percent even though it meant their workers took a 18 percent cut 
in their purchasing power the government said 
