<TEXT>
a savings and loan trade group called on 
federal regulators thursday to freeze the growth of walking 
dead thrift institutions that are insolvent but still open 
charles john koch chairman of the national council of savings 
institutions said at a news conference that the federal home loan 
bank board should bar 444 hopelessly insolvent sampls from making 
new loans 
koch said the bank board cannot practically close down all 
insolvent institutions immediately but it should take steps now to 
ensure that the insolvents do not hurt the profitability of the 
rest of the industry 
he said many insolvent institutions are betting on a decline in 
interest rates by pricing their loans at rates slightly under those 
offered by profitable institutions and paying slightly higher rates 
on deposits thus forcing the relatively healthy segment of the 
industry to narrow its profit margin 
our point is theyre not real people any more they 
shouldnt be allowed to compete with solvent institutions he 
said these walking dead are calling into question the 
ability of the remaining 85 percent of the industry to survive 
m danny wall chairman of the bank board said in an interview 
earlier this week that the agency is stepping up its enforcement of 
growth limits originally put on the books in 1985 
however koch complained that 105 of the 444 insolvent thrift 
associations were permitted to grow last year 32 of them faster 
than 10 percent 
mark clark a spokesman for the us league of savings 
institutions the largest sampl trade group said the league has been 
urging the bank board for three years to more strictly police 
growth regulations already in force 
sen william proxmire dwis chairman of the senate banking 
committee said earlier this week he will introduce a resolution 
calling for a freeze on deposit growth of insolvent sampls 
