<TEXT>
the government on thursday lifted 
price controls for many goods and services including energy and 
transport in a measure likely to fuel inflation and social 
tensions 
the widespread lifting of price controls at a time when 
inflation is hovering around 180 percent applies to those on 
gasoline diesel fuel electricity cooking gas coal rail 
transport and postal services 
these prices strictly controlled by the state for most of the 
post world war ii period will be formed freely by their producers 
the staterun press reported 
manufacturers of cooking oil flour and bread also were allowed 
price increases but the staples still will be under government 
control the reports said 
the government measure has already hit yugoslavs with a 39 
percent increase in the price of electricity an average 55 percent 
rise in the cost of rail transport and a 66 percent rise in the 
price of cooking oil 
other producers including those of fuel and bread have yet to 
announce their new prices 
workers have staged several protest marches following the 
introduction in may of a government program which allowed 
substantial price increases and hefty wage cuts 
the may measures lifted price controls for about 60 percent of 
goods and services which have been frozen since november 
the steps are designed to curb the countrys inflation and repay 
the 21 billion foreign debt by introducing a more marketoriented 
economy 
the government together with the international monetary fund 
which has helped in designing the program have set a target that 
yugoslav inflation should drop to 95 percent by the end of 1988 
the latest official evaluations however show that due to the 
wave of price increases prospects are dim that the target will be 
reached according to the most optimistic estimates yugoslavias 
annual inflation rate will be at least 130 percent by the end of 
1988 
the unpopular government measures are likely to contribute to a 
further decline in living standards which have already fallen by 
at least one third since 1980 labor unrest is also expected to 
grow 
anticipating the price increases most yugoslavs have been on a 
shopping spree in recent weeks for cooking oil and sugar causing 
shortages of those products 
