<TEXT>
the communist party said thursday that two 
prominent bolsheviks were innocent of antisoviet activity and 
political mistakes the charges josef stalin used to destroy them 
in the 1930s 
the report on the work of a commission of the ruling politburo 
distributed by the tass news agency was not a political 
rehabiliation of bolshevik leaders grigory zinoviev or lev kamenev 
but it indicated such a move probably was not far behind 
tass said the commission had received a report from the soviet 
supreme court which has cleared the names of several old 
bolsheviks this year and that it was continuing its work 
the party under mikhail s gorbachev has sought to clear the 
names of its leaders purged by stalin in the 1930s to erase his 
legacy of repression and assure party members they wont be 
punished for speaking their minds 
in june the supreme court cleared zinoviev kamenev karl radek 
and grigory pyatikov of criminal charges of which they were 
convicted in the 1930s zinoviev kamenev and pyatikov were shot 
and radek died in a prison camp 
among the first bolshevik leaders to be cleared was nikolai 
bukharin who in february was declared innocent of the charges for 
which he was shot on july 9 the politburo committee posthumously 
readmitted him to the party 
his case was considered important because gorbachevs reforms 
follow many of the concepts bukharin developed 
zinoviev and kamenev are not so strongly identified with 
particular policies as was bukharin but along with vladimir lenin 
leon trotsky and stalin were leaders of the bolshevik party when 
it seized power in 1917 
after first teaming up with stalin to eliminate all opposition 
zinoviev and kamenev were themselves accused in 193233 of heading 
an underground group seeking to reestablish capitalism 
it has been established that the investigation of this affair 
was carried out with gross violations of the law the report said 
it said zinoviev and kamenev never were told what charges they 
faced and that the materials of the affair contain no evidence 
of antisoviet activity 
concerning their political and theoretical views laid out in 
the program documents they were of a discussion character and did 
not contain appeals to replace undermine or weaken soviet power 
the report said 
when bukharin was readmitted to the party last month the 
committee said he had made political mistakes but they did not 
justify the criminal charges against him or his exclusion from the 
party 
the commission report contained a lengthy list of lesserknown 
bolshevik officials who also were shot or sentenced to prison 
during stalins purges 
they were tried for alleged membership in subversive groups that 
stalinist prosecutors called the union of marxistleninists 
the moscow center antisoviet trotskyzinoviev center and 
the parallel antisoviet trotsky center 
the report said prosecutors falsified evidence in a 1935 trial 
in which zinoviev kamenev and 19 others were accused of forming 
the moscow center it said prosecutors alleged the moscow 
center was an underground terrorist group led by zinoviev that 
helped plan the 1934 assassination of sergei kirov the popular 
leningrad party leader 
the memoirs of anastas mikoyan a bolshevik leader who survived 
the purges were published last year and said that resentment of 
stalin led some communists to try to replace him with kirov at a 
1934 party conference 
some historians believe stalin himself was behind the killing of 
kirov and that the dictator then accused his political opponents 
of planning the assassination as an excuse to have them shot 
there have been no steps toward the rehabiliation of trotsky 
stalins first and most serious opponent for power after the death 
of lenin in 1924 although some historians have suggested it 
trotsky was thrown out of the communist party banished from the 
country and murdered in mexico city in 1940 
