<TEXT>
at least one us city is seeing increased spinal 
cord injuries during the summer drought as swimmers dive into 
water thats not as deep as they think it is 
two spinal injury centers in milwaukee reported eight patients 
with neck and spinal cord injuries from diving into water june 1 to 
july 15 the national centers for disease control reported thursday 
that was up from three such injuries in the same period last 
year and five in the period in 1986 the cdc said 
this summers injured were males ages 15 to 23 one was hurt in 
a pool but the other seven were hurt diving into natural bodies of 
water all believed the water was deeper than it actually was 
the cdc said 
five of the seven were left with either partial or complete 
paralysis in both arms and both legs the other two suffered 
fractures but no residual neurologic problems 
this summers drought affecting most midwestern and many 
southern states has resulted in recordlow water levels in rivers 
lakes and streams the atlantabased cdc noted in its report 
these conditions probably increase the risk of spinal cord 
injuries from diving even in natural bodies of water previously 
considered safe 
for example the drought left wisconsins inland lakes 10 inches 
to 10 feet below normal the agency said 
because of extremely low water levels no one should dive 
even into a familiar body of water until the depth of the water 
has been objectively measured the cdc warned 
the cdc reported no current injury figures for the nation or for 
other cities however 10000 to 20000 spinal cord injuries occur 
in the united states each year with as many as 1000 from diving 
accidents the agency said 
several strategies for reducing such injuries have been 
suggested including the posting of warning signs during dry 
periods and campaigns to urge divers to check the depth of the 
water before diving in or at least jump feet first 
