michael dukakis campaigned in rural 
mississippi on thursday and said his promise of economi change 
would deliver opportunity to all no matter who they are or where 
they come from or what the color of their skin 
visiting near one of the civil rights battlegrounds of the 
1960s the democratic presidential nominee made only brief 
reference to that struggle for equality for blacks 
but he did say here in mississippi you know the importance 
of equal rights and civil rights today i say to all americans 
not just in neshoba county but all over america weve got to work 
together weve got to work together to bring down the barriers to 
opportunity for all our people 
dukakis spoke to a noontime crowd at the neshoba county fair 
where a crowd filled a grandstand and many more sat in lounge 
chairs on the red dirt of a horse track in front of the covered 
podium the mostly white audience was estimated at 6000 to 7000 
people by sheriff glen waddell 
the appearance was loaded with symbolism as the neshoba fair 
was the place where ronald reagan kicked off his campaign as the 
republican presidential nominee eight years ago nearly to the day 
dukakis has directed much of his campaign efforts since winning the 
nomination at attracting the support of independent and democratic 
voters who supported reagan in the past two elections 
at the same time he was campaigning in a state where he lost 
the democratic primary to jesse jackson 
the rural region of eastcentral mississippi was the scene of 
one of the dark incidents of the civil rights struggle the 1964 
slaying of three civil rights workers an episode that jackson 
frequently recalled in his campaign speeches 
dukakis didnt note in his remarks that the three mens bodies 
were found 24 years ago thursday asked about that later he said 
i talked about economic opportunity because thats the most 
important single thing that concerns people 
