<TEXT>
the senate began again thursday efforts to 
come up with a pentagon budget bill that president reagan will 
accept a day after reagan vetoed a military spending bill which he 
charged would weaken us defenses 
the senate started consideration of a bill appropriating 282 
billion for the pentagon although no votes or major debate were 
expected before friday 
reagan had vetoed a bill authorizing 2995 billion in pentagon 
spending for the fiscal year beginning oct 1 but indicated he 
might sign the companion appropriation measure 
in the complicated congressional budget process one set of 
legislation is passed to authorize spending and then separate 
measures are enacted to actually appropriate the money to pay for 
those authorized projects 
although the bill considered thursday appropriates 16 billion 
less than the measure rejected by reagan the appropriation measure 
essentially covers the same projects however the dollar totals 
are not as large because authorizing bills generally permit 
spending for more longrange projects amounts which are contained 
in the authorization measures 
two of reagans main objections to the authorization bill were 
its reductions in his request for star wars antimissile spending 
and arms control policy restrictions added by the democraticbacked 
congress 
the appropriations bill considered thursday contains the same 
cuts in star wars funds but none of the arms control restrictions 
however those restrictions could be added later 
when the senate passes its appropriation bill the measure will 
go to a housesenate conference committee to be reconciled with the 
similar bill enacted by the house six weeks ago 
earlier thursday leading conservatives said reagans veto of 
the defense bill had bolstered conservative support for the 
presidential candidacy of vice president george bush 
we told the president there was nothing he could have done 
that would have given our troops more of a shot in the arm than 
this veto edwin j fuelner jr president of the heritage 
foundation told reporters 
fuelner and other supporters of reagans military policies were 
interviewed outside the white house after meeting with the 
president in the cabinet room 
he will go out in our opinion the way president eisenhower 
did with a strong principled fight on an issue that will bring 
our people together fuelner said 
weve had trouble this summer getting people interested he 
said whatever the intention this piece of work the veto was a 
brilliant stroke because i havent seen people so excited in 
months 
reagan disavowed any partisan intent in vetoing the bill on 
wednesday 
also applauding the veto was retired lt gen daniel graham 
president of high frontier a principal supporter of the 
presidents star wars spacebased missile defense system 
graham said high frontier members are not only delighted that 
the president vetoed it they are delighted that george bush urged 
the veto and theyre delighted that george bush is taking a 
stronger stand on sdi 
the formal name of the star wars program is strategic defense 
initiative 
john tower of texas former republican chairman of the senate 
armed services committee said i think the president having 
vetoed the bill and having drawn the issue clearly is going to make 
it more politically perilous for the democratic majority in 
congress to repeat the bad legislation that appeared in this bill 
richard perle former assistant secretary of defense and now a 
fellow at the american enterprise institute said the key issue 
was the future of sdi this is not a dispute over details or 
precise funding levels the action taken by congress was 
intended to kill the program without taking political 
responsibility 
although the bill provided approximately the funds that reagan 
had requested administration officials say it would have crippled 
star wars by shifting funds away from the most promising areas of 
research 
kenneth adelman former director of the arms control and 
disarmament agency said the big message here is that bad 
national security is bad politics this was a bad national security 
bill and to veto it is good politics 
adelman saw the veto as the start of the issuefocused bush 
campaign and the staving off of creeping lame duckism for the 
reagan administration 
others attending the meeting included earl stock commander in 
chief of the veterans of foreign wars edwin rowny arms control 
adviser to the president dr edward teller the nuclear physicist 
and anna chennault president of tac international 
