<TEXT>
a major trade bill awaiting president reagans signature was 
labeled protectionist on thursday by several of americas leading 
trade partners who warned that the legislation could harm 
international relations 
the senate approved the bill wednesday by an 8511 vote the 
measure aimed at reviving us competitiveness abroad cleared the 
house of representatives earlier and president reagan has 
indicated he will sign it 
reagan vetoed a previous version of the bill in part because it 
contained a controversial plantclosing notification requirement 
earlier this week reagan decided not to veto a separate 
plantclosing bill 
major us trading partners stated their opposition to the trade 
bills provision that would make it easier for the us government 
to impose import curbs in retaliation for alleged unfair trading 
practices by other nations 
many of the nations that complained the bill is protectionist 
are accused by the united states of being protectionist themselves 
for using high tariffs quotas or other barriers to imports 
in the far east where the reaction was mostly negative the 
leaders of japan and south korea urged reagan to veto the bill 
japanese prime minister noboru takeshita said i think its 
unfortunate because the bill contains protectionist overtones 
trade minister hajime tamura said japan would monitor 
implementation of the bill to ensure it did not violate 
international trade regulations 
although the united states has registered trade deficits with 
each of east asias most powerful economies japan south korea 
taiwan and hong kong its biggest concern lies with japan last 
year 60 billion of the 170 billion us trade deficit lay with 
japan which has been the target of previous retaliatory sanctions 
south koreas foreign ministry issued a statement saying it 
deeply regretted the bills passage and called for its elimination 
it is the strong hope that the us administration will 
once again demonstrate its firm commitment to free trade by taking 
appropriate measures not to allow such a protectionist bill to be 
enacted the ministry said 
taiwans board of foreign trade said it was gravely 
concerned because the bill indicates the united states is going 
to move away from free trade and move to the practice of 
protectionism 
the bill extended the definition of unfair trade to the areas of 
exchange rate trade surplus labor rights and copyright 
violations the statement said 
in europe west germanys economics minister martin bangemann 
said the bill could turn out to be a strong burden on free 
international trade 
he appealed to the reagan administration to implement the 
policies outlined in the trade bill with as much restraint as 
possible 
even before the senate vote britains financial times said in 
an editorial that trading partners of the united states have 
reason to be nervous 
in their future dealings with the us administration they 
will almost certainly have to accept that it is armed with a tough 
new mandate to promote us exports by systematically forcing open 
foreign markets under threat of sanctions the newspaper said 
the british government had no immediate comment 
only officials in hong kong officials took a more positive view 
tony miller hong kongs acting trade director said the british 
colony welcomed the bill to the extent that it will reduce some 
of the pentup protectionist pressures in congress 
but hong kong officials also expressed concern about a provision 
calling for an investigation into unfair trade practices by foreign 
nations 
the bill also would bar japans toshiba corp from selling goods 
to the us government for three years as a penalty for a 
subsidiarys export of hightechnology milling machines to the 
soviet union 
the 50 percentowned subsidiary toshiba machine co also would 
be prohibited from selling products commercially in the united 
states for the same period 
joichi aoi president of toshiba corp said it was unacceptable 
that the us government planned to punish a foreign company that 
had not violated any american laws 
a company spokesman also quoted aoi as saying it was improper 
for the united states to impose a punishment for a past event with 
a new law 
the official who spoke on condition of anonymity estimated 
toshiba corp would suffer direct losses of about 50 million a 
year while indirect damage would be substantial 
</TEXT>
