<DOCNO> AP880804-0188 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
business productivity in the second quarter 
deteriorated at a rate unequalled since 1981 the government 
reported thursday prompting some analysts to predict major 
troubles ahead for the economys competitive vigor 
the efficiency of nonfarm businesses in producing goods and 
services declined 17 percent in april through june its first 
decrease since 1986 and the biggest decline since 1981 the labor 
departments bureau of labor statistics said 
productivity had risen at an annual rate of 34 percent in the 
first three months of 1988 and had been improving at a rate of 1 
percent to 2 percent annually in the previous three years 
reflecting the strong economic expansion output of goods and 
services by those businesses responsible for threefourths of us 
economic activity rose 47 percent in the second quarter 
but to achieve that growth companies increased their work hours 
by 65 percent hiring hundreds of thousands of new employees to 
send the unemployment rate to a 14year low of 53 percent 
to some extent the job growth is coming at the expense of 
productivity said larry chimerine president of the wfa group of 
bala cynwyd pa its the big issue because if this trend 
continues were not going to see any improvement in living 
standards 
allen sinai chief economist for the bston co a new york 
consulting firm said the deterioration in productivity is the 
first hard evidence of a shortage of skills among newly hired 
workers 
we are scraping the bottom of the barrel so to speak of new 
labor market entrants whose skills and training may not be 
sufficient for using the new data processing and communications 
technologies that are dominating service industries sinai said 
calling the development a major change from the past six or 
seven years sinai said a whole new range of government policies 
beyond fiscal and money supply management are now needed 
literacy retraining the ability to work with machines is 
now much more important to keeping inflation down and productivity 
up he said 
meanwhile the labor department said labor costs soared 59 
percent in the second quarter the largest gain since a 61 percent 
increase in the last quarter of 1986 as hourly wages and benefits 
rose at an annual rate of 41 percent 
after taking into account a 44 percent annual rate of inflation 
in the last 18 months workers purchasing power actually declined 
06 percent from april through june the department said 
its certainly not a sign that wages are accelerating or 
causing inflation said michael evans who runs a washington 
economic consulting firm 
evans and other private analysts said the quarterly figures are 
subject to revision and often fluctuate widely 
if you take the first two quarters together you have 
productivity improving at a rate of about 15 percent the first six 
months just like it has for several years now evans said if 
labor costs are rising 25 percent to 3 percent and wages are going 
up about 4 percent there is nothing inflationary in it 
while businesses generally suffered from poorer efficiency in 
the second quarter manufacturers continued to show improved 
productivity up 35 percent from the first quarter 
reflecting a boom in the industrial sector spawned by 
recordbreaking exports factory production soared 54 percent in 
the second quarter with only a 18 percent increase in the number 
of hours worked 
manufacturers also were much more successful in holding down 
factory wage and benefit increases allowing annual raises of only 
29 percent from april through june 
that enabled employers to reduce the labor costs of each item 
coming off their assembly lines by 06 percent even though it 
meant their workers took a 18 percent cut in purchasing power the 
government said 
