<TEXT>
robert page president and publisher of the 
chicago suntimes has resigned two years after spearheading a 
buyout of the newspaper from australian publisher rupert murdoch 
the paper announced thursday 
pages resignation was announced by suntimes chairman leonard 
p shaykin in a twopage press release that also said the company 
had repurchased pages shares in the corporation 
shaykin is managing partner of adler amp shaykin a new york 
investment firm that was one of the principle investors in the 
group page lined up to buy the suntimes for 145 million in june 
1986 
bob page has contributed much to the suntimes shaykin said 
in the statement he has now decided to pursue other interests 
all of us at the suntimes wish him well in whatever he chooses to 
do 
the paper also released a twopage statement by page 
i leave the suntimes with regret but with a strong management 
team and staff that as a newspaper is well positioned to continue 
its vital role as a unique and important chicago institution 
page said in the statement 
page had been president and publisher of the suntimes since 
1984 when murdochs news america publishing corp bought the paper 
from its longtime owners the field family of chicago 
the press release made no mention of a possible successor and 
the suntimes planned no further comment said spokeswoman marie 
mariorca 
the suntimes is second in circulation in the metropolitan 
chicago area to the chicago tribune with 625000 daily 
rumor of pages departure was reported sunday in the chicago 
tribune the newspaper citing unnamed sources said page had been 
at odds with shaykin over the financial performance of the 
suntimes but spokesmen for suntimes refused to comment on that 
report thursday 
when the paper was purchased from murdoch page promised a 
more serious more purposeful look at the time it was the 
nations 11th largest daily 
during pages tenure the newspaper hired several top 
journalists from the competing chicago tribune including current 
managing editor raymond coffey one of the biggest defectors was 
columnist ann landers who jumped to the tribune 
page was in the newsroom thursday when word of his resignation 
broke but slipped out of the building without talking to reporters 
waiting outside 
suntimes columnist irv kupcinet called page a good friend 
i think he lifted us up out of the morass of the rupert 
murdoch era kupcinet said i think we have a very solid 
future 
but one reporter who asked that his name not be used said 
lets just say page wont find too many broken hearts here 
page came to chicago after overseeing the revitalization of 
murdochs boston herald 
